REQUIREMENTS

1) GNU Scientific Library (http://www.gnu.org/software/gsl) development packages
   for your system (typically "gsl" and "gsl-devel").

2) LAPACK (http://www.netlib.org/lapack). It usually comes with GNU-Octave.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
INSTALLATION 

(More detailed information is included in the "tutorial",
available in the web page of the project.)

$ cd src
src$ runhaskell Setup.hs configure -p --prefix=$HOME
src$ runhaskell Setup.hs build
src$ runhaskell Setup.hs install --user

A local version of the documentation can be generated in src/dist/doc/html by

src$ runhaskell Setup.hs haddock


NOTE: The library must be used from another directory. For instance:

$ cd ../examples

Interactive:
------------

examples$ ghci
Prelude> :m + GSL
Prelude GSL> let quad = integrateQNG 1E-10
Loading package haskell98 ... linking ... done.
Loading package GSL-0.6 ... linking ... done.
Prelude GSL> quad (^2) 0 1
(0.3333333333333333,3.700743415417188e-15)
Prelude GSL> fst $ quad (\x->4/(1+x^2)) 0 1
3.141592653589793
Prelude GSL> pi
3.141592653589793
Prelude GSL> :q
Leaving GHCi.

examples$ ghci plot.hs
*Main> main

Compiled:
---------

examples$ ghc --make plot.hs
examples$ ./plot

Script:
-------

examples$ runhaskell plot.hs

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
USING ATLAS OPTIMIZED LIBRARIES AND LAPACK

The performance of some linear algebra computations with big matrices can
be significantly improved using ATLAS (http://math-atlas.sourceforge.net/).

They can be installed as a standalone package or as part of other systems.
For instance, GNU-Octave includes useful packages like atlas, lapack, fftw,
gnuplot, etc.

To use the optimized libraries you only need a symbolic link to the
appropriate atlas blas available in your distribution. For instance,
in my ubuntu distribution I have added:

~/lib/GSL-0.6/ghc-6.6/libcblas.so -> /usr/lib/atlas/libblas.so.3.0

In ubuntu I also need a symbolick link to the LAPACK library:

~/lib/GSL-0.6/ghc-6.6/liblapack.so -> /usr/lib/atlas/liblapack.so.3.0

